# AI Overview

The Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE) protocol is a tunneling protocol that encapsulates packets of one network protocol within another, creating virtual point-to-point or point-to-multipoint links over an IP network. Developed by Cisco Systems and defined by RFC 2784, GRE allows any OSI Layer 3 protocol (the "passenger" protocol) to be transported over a different IP network (the "carrier" protocol), forming a GRE tunnel. It is used to extend private networks across public infrastructure, connect geographically dispersed sites, and support protocols like multicast that might not otherwise be supported over a specific carrier network.
